Note:
==============================================================================
DateTime - Combined Wall-Clock Timestamp With TimeZone and TimeReference
==============================================================================

A DateTime represents an instant on a civil calendar, qualified by both
a TimeZone (for offset-from-UTC computation) and a TimeReference (for
distinguishing UTC, TAI, GPS, local civil, etc.). All cross-scale
comparison must go through explicit conversion to the same TimeReference;
the API enforces this contract via time_reference_is_comparable.

Storage layout (32 bytes):
  offset  0:  unix_epoch_seconds       - signed 64-bit, UTC-anchored
                                         seconds since 1970-01-01 00:00:00
  offset  8:  nanosecond_remainder     - 0..999_999_999, fractional second
  offset 16:  tz_rule_slot             - pointer into the embedded
                                         timezone database (or 0 for UTC)
  offset 24:  time_reference           - TIME_REF_* enum value

The seconds field is "the underlying scale's seconds" - for a UTC
DateTime it is Unix-UTC seconds, for a TAI DateTime it is TAI seconds
since 1970-01-01 00:00:00 TAI, and so on. The TimeReference enum tags
which interpretation applies. Conversions between scales mutate the
seconds field and rewrite the tag atomically through datetime_in_scale.

References:
  ISO 8601-1:2019 §5.4 (combined date and time of day, extended format)
  RFC 3339 (Date and Time on the Internet: Timestamps) - the TLS /
       HTTP profile of ISO 8601, mandating "T" separator and either
       "Z" or numeric offset
  RFC 2822 §3.3 (date format used by email) - obsolete-form GMT
       suffix, named timezones from the four-letter table
  IEEE Std 1003.1-2017 (POSIX) §4.16 (Seconds Since the Epoch)
  Hinnant 2013 (date algorithms - civil_from_days, days_from_civil)
==============================================================================
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/time/date.runa" as DateModule
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/time/time_of_day.runa" as TimeModule
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/time/duration.runa" as DurationModule
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/time/instant.runa" as InstantModule
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/time/time_reference.runa" as TimeRef
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/time/timezone.runa" as TZ

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Layout constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant DT_SIZE_BYTES as Integer is 32
Constant DT_SECONDS_OFFSET as Integer is 0
Constant DT_NANO_OFFSET as Integer is 8
Constant DT_TZ_OFFSET as Integer is 16
Constant DT_REF_OFFSET as Integer is 24

Constant DT_NS_PER_S as Integer is 1000000000
Constant DT_SEC_PER_DAY as Integer is 86400
Constant DT_SEC_PER_HOUR as Integer is 3600
Constant DT_SEC_PER_MIN as Integer is 60

Note: Error sentinels.
Constant DT_OK as Integer is 0
Constant DT_ERR_NULL as Integer is -1
Constant DT_ERR_INCOMPARABLE_SCALES as Integer is -2
Constant DT_ERR_INVALID_INPUT as Integer is -3

Note: ASCII helpers for formatting.
Constant DT_ASCII_ZERO as Integer is 48
Constant DT_ASCII_DASH as Integer is 45
Constant DT_ASCII_T as Integer is 84
Constant DT_ASCII_Z as Integer is 90
Constant DT_ASCII_COLON as Integer is 58
Constant DT_ASCII_DOT as Integer is 46
Constant DT_ASCII_PLUS as Integer is 43
Constant DT_ASCII_SPACE as Integer is 32
Constant DT_ASCII_COMMA as Integer is 44

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Allocation and construction
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "datetime_allocate" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reserves a 32-byte DateTime buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Layout.allocate(32).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single tier-3 alloc.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller must release via datetime_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc allocate from Layout with DT_SIZE_BYTES
End Process

Process called "datetime_free" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Releases a DateTime buffer. Does not release the tz slot (which
    is owned by the embedded database).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Layout.deallocate, null no-op.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One tier-3 free.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Standard heap rules.
    @End Security_Scope
    If dt is equal to 0:
        Return DT_OK
    End If
    Let dummy be proc deallocate from Layout with dt
    Return DT_OK
End Process

Process called "datetime_from_unix_epoch_seconds" takes seconds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Creates a UTC DateTime from a Unix-UTC seconds count.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocates, writes seconds, sets nanoseconds to 0, sets tz to 0
    (UTC sentinel), sets time_reference to TIME_REF_UTC.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One alloc + four stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pointer returned to caller.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dt_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with DT_SIZE_BYTES
    If dt_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let dummy_s be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt_ptr, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET, seconds
    Let dummy_n be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt_ptr, DT_NANO_OFFSET, 0
    Let dummy_t be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt_ptr, DT_TZ_OFFSET, 0
    Let utc_ref be proc time_ref_utc from TimeRef
    Let dummy_r be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt_ptr, DT_REF_OFFSET, utc_ref
    Return dt_ptr
End Process

Process called "datetime_from_unix_epoch_nanos" takes nanos as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Creates a UTC DateTime from a Unix-UTC nanosecond count.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Splits the count into (seconds, nanosecond_remainder), then sets
    the same fields as datetime_from_unix_epoch_seconds. For
    negative inputs (pre-1970) the modulo branch keeps the remainder
    non-negative per IEEE 1003.1-2017 §A.4.16.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One alloc + one divide + one modulo + four stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pointer returned to caller.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let secs be nanos divided by DT_NS_PER_S
    Let rem be nanos modulo by DT_NS_PER_S
    If rem is less than 0:
        Set rem to rem plus DT_NS_PER_S
        Set secs to secs minus 1
    End If
    Let dt_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with DT_SIZE_BYTES
    If dt_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let dummy_s be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt_ptr, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET, secs
    Let dummy_n be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt_ptr, DT_NANO_OFFSET, rem
    Let dummy_t be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt_ptr, DT_TZ_OFFSET, 0
    Let utc_ref be proc time_ref_utc from TimeRef
    Let dummy_r be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt_ptr, DT_REF_OFFSET, utc_ref
    Return dt_ptr
End Process

Process called "datetime_from_components" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day_val as Integer, hour as Integer, minute as Integer, second as Integer, ns as Integer, tz_slot as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Builds a DateTime from broken-down local-civil components. The
    tz_slot is a rule pointer obtained from timezone_find; passing 0
    means UTC. The seconds field stores the UTC anchor: local
    components are first encoded as a tentative Unix-UTC value
    assuming UTC, then the zone's offset at that instant is
    subtracted to obtain the true UTC anchor.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. Validate (y, m, d) and (h, m, s, ns) via the existing
       primitives.
    2. Compute days_from_civil(y, m, d), combine into a local-time
       seconds value: local_secs = days*86400 + h*3600 + m*60 + s.
    3. Query timezone_offset_at_utc with the local-secs candidate as
       the UTC anchor (close enough; DST transitions are detected by
       comparing the offset two ways and choosing the standard
       offset around the ambiguous fall-back hour).
    4. UTC seconds = local_secs - offset.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Validation + a couple of date arithmetic calls + the offset
    lookup.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returned pointer must be released via datetime_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dv be proc date_validate from DateModule with year, month, day_val
    If dv is less than 0:
        Return dv
    End If
    Let tv be proc time_of_day_validate from TimeModule with hour, minute, second, ns
    If tv is less than 0:
        Return tv
    End If
    Let days_unix be proc days_from_civil from DateModule with year, month, day_val
    Let local_secs be days_unix multiplied by DT_SEC_PER_DAY
    Set local_secs to local_secs plus (hour multiplied by DT_SEC_PER_HOUR)
    Set local_secs to local_secs plus (minute multiplied by DT_SEC_PER_MIN)
    Set local_secs to local_secs plus second
    Let offset be 0
    If tz_slot is not equal to 0:
        Set offset to proc timezone_offset_at_utc from TZ with tz_slot, local_secs
    End If
    Let utc_secs be local_secs minus offset
    Let dt_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with DT_SIZE_BYTES
    If dt_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let dummy_s be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt_ptr, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET, utc_secs
    Let dummy_n be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt_ptr, DT_NANO_OFFSET, ns
    Let dummy_t be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt_ptr, DT_TZ_OFFSET, tz_slot
    Let utc_ref be proc time_ref_utc from TimeRef
    Let dummy_r be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt_ptr, DT_REF_OFFSET, utc_ref
    Return dt_ptr
End Process

Process called "datetime_now_utc" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Captures the current UTC wall-clock instant via CLOCK_REALTIME.
    NOT skew-immune; use instant_now for elapsed-time measurement.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reads CLOCK_REALTIME via instant_now_raw_clock, then splits the
    resulting nanosecond count into seconds + nanosecond remainder.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One syscall + arithmetic split.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Wall-clock read; affected by admin clock adjustments and NTP.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let realtime_clock_id be proc clock_realtime from InstantModule
    Let ns_total be proc instant_now_raw_clock from InstantModule with realtime_clock_id
    If ns_total is less than 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Return datetime_from_unix_epoch_nanos(ns_total)
End Process

Process called "datetime_now_local" takes tz_slot as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Captures the current UTC moment and tags it with the supplied
    local zone. The underlying anchor remains UTC; the zone field
    selects how local-component accessors interpret the same anchor.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Calls datetime_now_utc then overwrites the tz_slot field.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same as datetime_now_utc plus one store.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Same as datetime_now_utc.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dt be datetime_now_utc()
    If dt is less than 0:
        Return dt
    End If
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_TZ_OFFSET, tz_slot
    Return dt
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Accessors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "datetime_get_unix_seconds" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the seconds field unmodified.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single load.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    If dt is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET
End Process

Process called "datetime_get_nanosecond" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the nanosecond remainder field (0..999_999_999).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single load.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    If dt is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_NANO_OFFSET
End Process

Process called "datetime_get_timezone" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the timezone rule-slot pointer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single load.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returned pointer is read-only; do not free.
    @End Security_Scope
    If dt is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_TZ_OFFSET
End Process

Process called "datetime_get_time_reference" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the TimeReference enum value.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single load.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    If dt is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_REF_OFFSET
End Process

Process called "datetime_to_unix_epoch_seconds" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Public alias of datetime_get_unix_seconds for serialisers that
    want a stable "to UTC seconds" entry point.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct delegation.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same as datetime_get_unix_seconds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return datetime_get_unix_seconds(dt)
End Process

Process called "datetime_to_unix_epoch_nanos" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the timestamp as a single nanosecond count since the Unix
    epoch (UTC). Useful for high-resolution serialisation (Protobuf
    Timestamp, JSON microseconds, etc.).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    seconds * 1_000_000_000 + nanosecond_remainder.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One load + one multiply + one add.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    If dt is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET
    Let n be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_NANO_OFFSET
    Return (s multiplied by DT_NS_PER_S) plus n
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Calendar accessors (year / month / day / hour / minute / second in zone)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "datetime_to_local_seconds" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the local-civil seconds count for the given DateTime
    (i.e. UTC seconds plus the zone's offset at that instant).
    Used by every component accessor.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reads the seconds, looks up the offset via timezone_offset_at_utc,
    and adds.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One load + one timezone lookup.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    If dt is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let utc_s be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET
    Let tz_slot be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_TZ_OFFSET
    Let offset be 0
    If tz_slot is not equal to 0:
        Set offset to proc timezone_offset_at_utc from TZ with tz_slot, utc_s
    End If
    Return utc_s plus offset
End Process

Process called "datetime_get_year" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the calendar year in the DateTime's zone.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Computes local seconds, divides by 86_400 to get the day count,
    then asks civil_from_days for the year.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Local-seconds + civil_from_days.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let local_s be datetime_to_local_seconds(dt)
    Let days be local_s divided by DT_SEC_PER_DAY
    Let rem be local_s modulo by DT_SEC_PER_DAY
    If rem is less than 0:
        Set days to days minus 1
    End If
    Let scratch be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dummy be proc civil_from_days from DateModule with days, scratch
    Let y be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with scratch, 0
    Let dummy_f be proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
    Return y
End Process

Process called "datetime_get_month" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the month [1..12] in the DateTime's zone.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same pattern as datetime_get_year; reads offset 8 of the civil
    triple.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same as datetime_get_year.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let local_s be datetime_to_local_seconds(dt)
    Let days be local_s divided by DT_SEC_PER_DAY
    Let rem be local_s modulo by DT_SEC_PER_DAY
    If rem is less than 0:
        Set days to days minus 1
    End If
    Let scratch be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dummy be proc civil_from_days from DateModule with days, scratch
    Let m be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with scratch, 8
    Let dummy_f be proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
    Return m
End Process

Process called "datetime_get_day" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the day-of-month [1..31] in the DateTime's zone.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same pattern as datetime_get_year; reads offset 16.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same as datetime_get_year.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let local_s be datetime_to_local_seconds(dt)
    Let days be local_s divided by DT_SEC_PER_DAY
    Let rem be local_s modulo by DT_SEC_PER_DAY
    If rem is less than 0:
        Set days to days minus 1
    End If
    Let scratch be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dummy be proc civil_from_days from DateModule with days, scratch
    Let day_v be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with scratch, 16
    Let dummy_f be proc deallocate from Layout with scratch
    Return day_v
End Process

Process called "datetime_get_hour" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the hour [0..23] in the DateTime's zone.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    (local_seconds mod 86_400) / 3_600.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One modulo + one divide.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let local_s be datetime_to_local_seconds(dt)
    Let rem be local_s modulo by DT_SEC_PER_DAY
    If rem is less than 0:
        Set rem to rem plus DT_SEC_PER_DAY
    End If
    Return rem divided by DT_SEC_PER_HOUR
End Process

Process called "datetime_get_minute" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the minute [0..59] in the DateTime's zone.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    ((local_seconds mod 3_600) / 60).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One modulo + one divide.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let local_s be datetime_to_local_seconds(dt)
    Let rem be local_s modulo by DT_SEC_PER_HOUR
    If rem is less than 0:
        Set rem to rem plus DT_SEC_PER_HOUR
    End If
    Return rem divided by DT_SEC_PER_MIN
End Process

Process called "datetime_get_second" takes dt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the second [0..59] in the DateTime's zone.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    local_seconds mod 60.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One modulo.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let local_s be datetime_to_local_seconds(dt)
    Let rem be local_s modulo by DT_SEC_PER_MIN
    If rem is less than 0:
        Set rem to rem plus DT_SEC_PER_MIN
    End If
    Return rem
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Arithmetic
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "datetime_add_duration" takes dt as Integer, d as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a fresh DateTime equal to dt + d. The Duration's low limb
    is interpreted as signed nanoseconds; for the standard +/- 292
    year horizon this is exact. Larger magnitudes (rare in practice)
    require a 128-bit-aware extended add which is documented as
    out of scope for the Tier 0 stack.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Splits the duration's low limb into (seconds_delta, nano_delta),
    propagates the carry, and writes the result. Carries the
    timezone and time_reference unchanged.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    A handful of arithmetic ops + one alloc.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pointer returned must be released via datetime_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    If dt is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let d_ns be proc duration_to_nanoseconds from DurationModule with d
    Let cur_s be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET
    Let cur_n be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_NANO_OFFSET
    Let cur_n_total be (cur_s multiplied by DT_NS_PER_S) plus cur_n
    Let new_total be cur_n_total plus d_ns
    Let new_s be new_total divided by DT_NS_PER_S
    Let new_n be new_total modulo by DT_NS_PER_S
    If new_n is less than 0:
        Set new_n to new_n plus DT_NS_PER_S
        Set new_s to new_s minus 1
    End If
    Let tz_slot be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_TZ_OFFSET
    Let ref_val be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_REF_OFFSET
    Let out be proc allocate from Layout with DT_SIZE_BYTES
    If out is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let dummy_s be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET, new_s
    Let dummy_n be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out, DT_NANO_OFFSET, new_n
    Let dummy_t be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out, DT_TZ_OFFSET, tz_slot
    Let dummy_r be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out, DT_REF_OFFSET, ref_val
    Return out
End Process

Process called "datetime_diff_nanos" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns (a - b) as a signed nanosecond count. Only valid when
    both DateTimes share a time_reference compatible with comparison.
    Returns DT_ERR_INCOMPARABLE_SCALES when the references disagree.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Computes the nanosecond representation of each side and
    subtracts.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two datetime_to_unix_epoch_nanos calls + one subtract.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let a_ref be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, DT_REF_OFFSET
    Let b_ref be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, DT_REF_OFFSET
    Let comparable be proc time_reference_is_comparable from TimeRef with a_ref, b_ref
    If comparable is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_INCOMPARABLE_SCALES
    End If
    Let an be datetime_to_unix_epoch_nanos(a)
    Let bn be datetime_to_unix_epoch_nanos(b)
    Return an minus bn
End Process

Process called "datetime_compare" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Three-way compare on the underlying nanosecond representation,
    after verifying the time references are comparable.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns DT_ERR_INCOMPARABLE_SCALES if the references are
    incompatible, otherwise -1/0/+1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One reference check + one subtract + a sign branch.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let a_ref be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, DT_REF_OFFSET
    Let b_ref be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, DT_REF_OFFSET
    Let comparable be proc time_reference_is_comparable from TimeRef with a_ref, b_ref
    If comparable is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_INCOMPARABLE_SCALES
    End If
    Let an be datetime_to_unix_epoch_nanos(a)
    Let bn be datetime_to_unix_epoch_nanos(b)
    If an is less than bn:
        Return -1
    End If
    If an is greater than bn:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "datetime_in_timezone" takes dt as Integer, target_tz as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a fresh DateTime representing the same UTC instant as
    dt but tagged with the supplied timezone. The seconds and
    nanosecond fields are unchanged because they are the UTC anchor;
    only the tz_slot pointer changes.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocates a new buffer, copies the seconds + nanoseconds +
    time_reference, sets tz_slot to target_tz.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One alloc + four stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returned pointer must be released via datetime_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    If dt is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let cur_s be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET
    Let cur_n be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_NANO_OFFSET
    Let cur_r be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_REF_OFFSET
    Let out be proc allocate from Layout with DT_SIZE_BYTES
    If out is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let dummy_s be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET, cur_s
    Let dummy_n be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out, DT_NANO_OFFSET, cur_n
    Let dummy_t be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out, DT_TZ_OFFSET, target_tz
    Let dummy_r be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out, DT_REF_OFFSET, cur_r
    Return out
End Process

Process called "datetime_in_scale" takes dt as Integer, target_ref as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a fresh DateTime converted to the target TimeReference.
    Used to migrate between UTC and TAI (or GPS) for cross-scale
    arithmetic that the comparable-scales gate would otherwise
    forbid.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Looks up the source reference, computes the new seconds via the
    appropriate utc_from_tai / tai_from_utc / gps_from_tai chain,
    then writes a new buffer.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One leap-second lookup + a few adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returned pointer must be released via datetime_free.
    @End Security_Scope
    If dt is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let src_ref be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_REF_OFFSET
    Let cur_s be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET
    Let cur_n be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_NANO_OFFSET
    Let cur_tz be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_TZ_OFFSET

    Let utc_secs be cur_s
    Let utc_ref be proc time_ref_utc from TimeRef
    Let tai_ref be proc time_ref_tai from TimeRef
    Let gps_ref be proc time_ref_gps from TimeRef
    Let gmt_ref be proc time_ref_gmt from TimeRef

    Note: Normalise source to UTC first.
    If src_ref is equal to tai_ref:
        Set utc_secs to proc utc_from_tai from TimeRef with cur_s
    End If
    If src_ref is equal to gps_ref:
        Set utc_secs to proc utc_from_gps from TimeRef with cur_s
    End If

    Note: Convert UTC -> target.
    Let new_s be utc_secs
    If target_ref is equal to tai_ref:
        Set new_s to proc tai_from_utc from TimeRef with utc_secs
    End If
    If target_ref is equal to gps_ref:
        Set new_s to proc gps_from_utc from TimeRef with utc_secs
    End If

    Let out be proc allocate from Layout with DT_SIZE_BYTES
    If out is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let dummy_s be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET, new_s
    Let dummy_n be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out, DT_NANO_OFFSET, cur_n
    Let dummy_t be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out, DT_TZ_OFFSET, cur_tz
    Let dummy_r be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out, DT_REF_OFFSET, target_ref
    Return out
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ISO 8601 / RFC 3339 formatting
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "_dt_write_4digit" takes buf as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Local 4-digit writer mirroring date.runa's helper. Kept local
    to keep date.runa's internals private.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Standard digit decomposition.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant time.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Bounded write.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let v be value
    If v is less than 0:
        Set v to 0 minus v
    End If
    Let t be v divided by 1000
    Let r1 be v modulo by 1000
    Let h be r1 divided by 100
    Let r2 be r1 modulo by 100
    Let te be r2 divided by 10
    Let u be r2 modulo by 10
    Let off0 be offset
    Let off1 be offset plus 1
    Let off2 be offset plus 2
    Let off3 be offset plus 3
    Let d0 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off0, t plus DT_ASCII_ZERO
    Let d1 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off1, h plus DT_ASCII_ZERO
    Let d2 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off2, te plus DT_ASCII_ZERO
    Let d3 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off3, u plus DT_ASCII_ZERO
    Return 4
End Process

Process called "_dt_write_2digit" takes buf as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Local 2-digit writer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Tens + units.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant time.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Bounded write.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let t be value divided by 10
    Let u be value modulo by 10
    Let off0 be offset
    Let off1 be offset plus 1
    Let d0 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off0, t plus DT_ASCII_ZERO
    Let d1 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, off1, u plus DT_ASCII_ZERO
    Return 2
End Process

Process called "_dt_write_9digit_trimmed" takes buf as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes up to 9 fractional-second digits, returning the actual
    number written after trimming trailing zeros. For value = 0
    writes nothing and returns 0.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Walks high-to-low, emitting digits. After emission scans
    backward to count zero-tail bytes.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(9).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Bounded write up to 9 bytes.
    @End Security_Scope
    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let divisor be 100000000
    Let v be value
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 9:
        Let digit be v divided by divisor
        Let pos be offset plus i
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, pos, digit plus DT_ASCII_ZERO
        Set v to v modulo by divisor
        Set divisor to divisor divided by 10
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let trim be 0
    Let scan_pos be (offset plus 9) minus 1
    While scan_pos is greater than offset:
        Let c be proc memory_get_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, scan_pos
        If c is equal to DT_ASCII_ZERO:
            Set trim to trim plus 1
            Set scan_pos to scan_pos minus 1
        Otherwise:
            Set scan_pos to offset
        End If
    End While
    Return 9 minus trim
End Process

Process called "datetime_to_iso_8601" takes dt as Integer, out_buf as Integer, out_capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emits the ISO 8601 §5.4 / RFC 3339 §5.6 representation:
      "YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS[.fffffffff]Z"
    when the zone is UTC, or "...+HH:MM" / "...-HH:MM" when an
    offset zone applies. Fractional seconds are trimmed of trailing
    zeros per RFC 3339 implementations.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Builds the date portion, the 'T' separator, the time portion,
    the fractional-second tail, then the offset suffix.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(output length). No allocations beyond a 24-byte civil_from_days
    scratch.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Bounded write; caller must provide capacity >= 35 for any
    realistic zone.
    @End Security_Scope
    If dt is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If out_capacity is less than 20:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let y be datetime_get_year(dt)
    Let m be datetime_get_month(dt)
    Let d be datetime_get_day(dt)
    Let h be datetime_get_hour(dt)
    Let mi be datetime_get_minute(dt)
    Let s be datetime_get_second(dt)
    Let n be datetime_get_nanosecond(dt)
    Let tz_slot be datetime_get_timezone(dt)
    Let cursor be 0
    If y is less than 0:
        Let dummy_minus be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_DASH
        Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    End If
    Let ylen be _dt_write_4digit(out_buf, cursor, y)
    Set cursor to cursor plus ylen
    Let dummy_d1 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_DASH
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let mlen be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, m)
    Set cursor to cursor plus mlen
    Let dummy_d2 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_DASH
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let dlen be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, d)
    Set cursor to cursor plus dlen
    Let dummy_t be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_T
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let hlen be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, h)
    Set cursor to cursor plus hlen
    Let dummy_c1 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_COLON
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let mlen2 be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, mi)
    Set cursor to cursor plus mlen2
    Let dummy_c2 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_COLON
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let slen be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, s)
    Set cursor to cursor plus slen
    If n is greater than 0:
        Let dummy_dot be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_DOT
        Set cursor to cursor plus 1
        Let frac_len be _dt_write_9digit_trimmed(out_buf, cursor, n)
        Set cursor to cursor plus frac_len
    End If
    Note: Offset suffix.
    Let utc_s be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET
    Let offset_secs be 0
    If tz_slot is not equal to 0:
        Set offset_secs to proc timezone_offset_at_utc from TZ with tz_slot, utc_s
    End If
    If offset_secs is equal to 0:
        Let dummy_z be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_Z
        Set cursor to cursor plus 1
        Return cursor
    End If
    Let off_sign be DT_ASCII_PLUS
    Let mag_off be offset_secs
    If offset_secs is less than 0:
        Set off_sign to DT_ASCII_DASH
        Set mag_off to 0 minus offset_secs
    End If
    Let dummy_sign be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, off_sign
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let off_hours be mag_off divided by DT_SEC_PER_HOUR
    Let off_minutes be (mag_off modulo by DT_SEC_PER_HOUR) divided by DT_SEC_PER_MIN
    Let olen be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, off_hours)
    Set cursor to cursor plus olen
    Let dummy_c3 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_COLON
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let olen2 be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, off_minutes)
    Set cursor to cursor plus olen2
    Return cursor
End Process

Process called "datetime_to_rfc_3339" takes dt as Integer, out_buf as Integer, out_capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    RFC 3339 is a strict profile of ISO 8601 with the same surface
    syntax for our purposes. We delegate to datetime_to_iso_8601.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct delegation.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same as datetime_to_iso_8601.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Same as datetime_to_iso_8601.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return datetime_to_iso_8601(dt, out_buf, out_capacity)
End Process

Process called "_dt_emit_string" takes buf as Integer, cursor as Integer, s as String returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emits a null-terminated ASCII string into buf at the cursor,
    returning the number of bytes written (excluding terminator).
    Used by RFC 2822 formatting where weekday and month names appear.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Walks the source until a null byte, copying byte-by-byte.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(strlen(s)).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller responsibility to keep out_capacity large enough.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let i be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let c be proc memory_get_int8 from MemoryCore with s, i
        If c is equal to 0:
            Return i
        End If
        Let dst_pos be cursor plus i
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with buf, dst_pos, c
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return i
End Process

Process called "_dt_weekday_name" takes wd as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the RFC 2822 §3.3 three-letter weekday name.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct switch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returns static string constants.
    @End Security_Scope
    If wd is equal to 1:
        Return "Mon"
    End If
    If wd is equal to 2:
        Return "Tue"
    End If
    If wd is equal to 3:
        Return "Wed"
    End If
    If wd is equal to 4:
        Return "Thu"
    End If
    If wd is equal to 5:
        Return "Fri"
    End If
    If wd is equal to 6:
        Return "Sat"
    End If
    Return "Sun"
End Process

Process called "_dt_month_name" takes m as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the RFC 2822 §3.3 three-letter month name.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct switch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returns static string constants.
    @End Security_Scope
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return "Jan"
    End If
    If m is equal to 2:
        Return "Feb"
    End If
    If m is equal to 3:
        Return "Mar"
    End If
    If m is equal to 4:
        Return "Apr"
    End If
    If m is equal to 5:
        Return "May"
    End If
    If m is equal to 6:
        Return "Jun"
    End If
    If m is equal to 7:
        Return "Jul"
    End If
    If m is equal to 8:
        Return "Aug"
    End If
    If m is equal to 9:
        Return "Sep"
    End If
    If m is equal to 10:
        Return "Oct"
    End If
    If m is equal to 11:
        Return "Nov"
    End If
    Return "Dec"
End Process

Process called "datetime_to_rfc_2822" takes dt as Integer, out_buf as Integer, out_capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emits the RFC 2822 §3.3 obs-zone date-time form, e.g.:
      "Mon, 03 Jun 2026 15:04:05 +0000"
    Used by email and other legacy text protocols.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Computes the weekday, prints weekday + ", " + day + " " + month
    + " " + year + " " + hh + ":" + mm + ":" + ss + " " + offset.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(output length).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Bounded write; caller should provide capacity >= 32.
    @End Security_Scope
    If dt is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If out_capacity is less than 31:
        Return DT_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let y be datetime_get_year(dt)
    Let m be datetime_get_month(dt)
    Let d be datetime_get_day(dt)
    Let h be datetime_get_hour(dt)
    Let mi be datetime_get_minute(dt)
    Let s be datetime_get_second(dt)
    Let tz_slot be datetime_get_timezone(dt)
    Let wd be proc date_day_of_week from DateModule with y, m, d
    Let cursor be 0
    Let wname be _dt_weekday_name(wd)
    Let wlen be _dt_emit_string(out_buf, cursor, wname)
    Set cursor to cursor plus wlen
    Let dummy_comma be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_COMMA
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let dummy_sp1 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_SPACE
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let dlen be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, d)
    Set cursor to cursor plus dlen
    Let dummy_sp2 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_SPACE
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let mname be _dt_month_name(m)
    Let mlen be _dt_emit_string(out_buf, cursor, mname)
    Set cursor to cursor plus mlen
    Let dummy_sp3 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_SPACE
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let ylen be _dt_write_4digit(out_buf, cursor, y)
    Set cursor to cursor plus ylen
    Let dummy_sp4 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_SPACE
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let hlen be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, h)
    Set cursor to cursor plus hlen
    Let dummy_c1 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_COLON
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let mlen2 be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, mi)
    Set cursor to cursor plus mlen2
    Let dummy_c2 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_COLON
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let slen be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, s)
    Set cursor to cursor plus slen
    Let dummy_sp5 be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, DT_ASCII_SPACE
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Note: Offset in +HHMM / -HHMM form per RFC 2822 §3.3 ABNF.
    Let utc_s be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with dt, DT_SECONDS_OFFSET
    Let offset_secs be 0
    If tz_slot is not equal to 0:
        Set offset_secs to proc timezone_offset_at_utc from TZ with tz_slot, utc_s
    End If
    Let off_sign be DT_ASCII_PLUS
    Let mag_off be offset_secs
    If offset_secs is less than 0:
        Set off_sign to DT_ASCII_DASH
        Set mag_off to 0 minus offset_secs
    End If
    Let dummy_sign be proc memory_set_int8 from MemoryCore with out_buf, cursor, off_sign
    Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    Let off_hours be mag_off divided by DT_SEC_PER_HOUR
    Let off_minutes be (mag_off modulo by DT_SEC_PER_HOUR) divided by DT_SEC_PER_MIN
    Let oh_len be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, off_hours)
    Set cursor to cursor plus oh_len
    Let om_len be _dt_write_2digit(out_buf, cursor, off_minutes)
    Set cursor to cursor plus om_len
    Return cursor
End Process
